    "comment": "Rationale: Figure 2a, 3e: immunofluorescence imaging of hippocampal neurons stained for endogenous ELMO1 and PSD95 (DLG4) showed partial co-localization. Overexpressed GFP-ELMO1 localized to dendrites and spines apposed to presynaptic terminals labeled by anti-SV2.\n\nFigure 2c-d, 3: confocal imaging showed that ELMO1 shRNA knockdown reduced dendritic spine density in hippocampal neurons and overexpression of the ELMO1 C-terminus promoted spine morphogenesis.\n\nFigure 4: ELMO and Dock180 (DOCK1) form a complex in hippocampal neurons and function through activating Rac1.\n\nFigure 5-7: RhoG is required for spine formation, its activation leads to increased spine head size and functions through the ELMO1/Dock180/Rac pathway.. Experimental description: M&M: \"Neuronal Culture and Transfection - Hippocampal neuron cultures were prepared from embryonic day 19 rat embryos as described previously\"\n\nantibody:\nrabbit polyclonal anti-Dock180 (1:1000, provided by Dr. Matsuda)\ngoat polyclonal anti-Dock180 antibodies (1:100, N19 and C19, Santa Cruz Biotechnology)\nrabbit polyclonal anti-ELMO1 (1:1000, provided by Dr. Ravichandran)\ngoat polyclonal anti-ELMO1 (1:2000, Abcam)",
